00:02:13.550 --> 00:02:16.140
This is our second cookbook
from "Lucky Peach."

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:20.440
Our first one was a book called
"101 Easy Asian Recipes,"

00:02:20.440 --> 00:02:23.400
which was originally a joke.

00:02:23.400 --> 00:02:25.650
We were going to make this
book called "101 Easy Asian

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:29.320
Recipes," and it was going to
be 101 super difficult recipes

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:31.280
that no one could pull off.

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:35.550
But somewhere along the
line, we grew up a little bit

00:02:35.550 --> 00:02:38.670
and decided that helping people
cook at home was important,

00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:42.640
and that kind of making
esoteric jokes that only

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:44.200
we thought were
funny was not really

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:45.408
that helpful to anybody else.

00:02:45.408 --> 00:02:49.190
So this book is the
second one we've made,

00:02:49.190 --> 00:02:54.200
and the first in a series
of single-subject cookbooks.

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:57.140
So I don't know if you guys are
familiar with the "Time Life"

00:02:57.140 --> 00:02:58.659
cookbooks that were
sort of covered,

00:02:58.659 --> 00:03:00.700
you know, a single cuisine
from around the world,

00:03:00.700 --> 00:03:01.760
or a single ingredient.

00:03:01.760 --> 00:03:05.730
Or the "River Cottage"
series-- or, like, Alice Waters

00:03:05.730 --> 00:03:09.910
has done books about just
vegetables, or just fruits.

00:03:09.910 --> 00:03:13.520
Those are sort of
spirit animals.

00:03:13.520 --> 00:03:16.750
Those are what we love
and are inspired by.

00:03:16.750 --> 00:03:20.240
But this book is nothing
like that whatsoever.

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:23.650
It is not comprehensive,
or exhaustive,

00:03:23.650 --> 00:03:28.050
or nearly as intelligent as
those books are-- primarily

00:03:28.050 --> 00:03:29.430
because I wrote most of it.

00:03:29.430 --> 00:03:32.405
So it's just not that smart.

00:03:32.405 --> 00:03:34.280
No, I keep on describing
this series of books

00:03:34.280 --> 00:03:37.700
as a series of
books that you could

00:03:37.700 --> 00:03:40.000
enjoy reading in the
bathroom and then

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:41.272
find useful in the kitchen.

00:03:41.272 --> 00:03:43.730
One of the few items that you
could bring between those two

00:03:43.730 --> 00:03:46.390
rooms safely.

00:03:46.390 --> 00:03:47.740
So anyway, that is the book.

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:52.070
It's all about sausages.

00:03:52.070 --> 00:03:54.490
And the reason why we decided
to make a book entirely

00:03:54.490 --> 00:03:57.530
about sausages, to be
honest with you, mostly

00:03:57.530 --> 00:04:01.820
has to do with the fact that the
title was really funny to us.

00:04:01.820 --> 00:04:04.024
"The Wurst of Lucky Peach"
was sort of too good

00:04:04.024 --> 00:04:05.440
of a pun to pass
up, so we decided

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:09.130
make this book about sausages.

00:04:09.130 --> 00:04:11.840
And at first, when I sat down to
kind of put this book together,

00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:15.500
I thought, wow, this is
way too narrow of a topic.

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:19.220
Like, not that many people
care that much about sausage.

00:04:19.220 --> 00:04:22.935
Why are we doing a book
entirely about sausages?

00:04:22.935 --> 00:04:25.240
Then I started
thinking more about it.

00:04:25.240 --> 00:04:28.237
And it started to be like
when you learn a new word,

00:04:28.237 --> 00:04:29.820
and all of a sudden,
everyone you know

00:04:29.820 --> 00:04:31.220
has been using this
word for years,

00:04:31.220 --> 00:04:33.350
and you just have not understood
what they were saying.

00:04:33.350 --> 00:04:34.880
And it was like
that with sausages,

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:37.230
where all of a sudden,
everywhere I would go, I'd be,

00:04:37.230 --> 00:04:39.650
like, oh, man, we
eat a lot of sausage.

00:04:39.650 --> 00:04:43.060
Like, we really like
sausages in this country

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:44.320
and around the world.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:47.840
And I started thinking
more and more about sausage

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:51.050
not as this joke thing, or not
as this kind of niche food,

00:04:51.050 --> 00:04:57.260
but more as an important part
of our culinary cultures.

00:04:57.260 --> 00:04:59.870
And that goes sort
around the world.

00:04:59.870 --> 00:05:03.520
Anywhere that you've had people
who eat meat, and have had

00:05:03.520 --> 00:05:06.370
to worry about where food is
going to come from tomorrow,

00:05:06.370 --> 00:05:08.870
or the next day-- or what
to do with this animal

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:11.610
that they just slaughtered,
and have all this extra meat--

00:05:11.610 --> 00:05:17.060
or anywhere there's been a
lower socioeconomic class that

00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:18.960
hasn't had access
to sort of the,

00:05:18.960 --> 00:05:22.100
you know, filet
mignon and tenderloin,

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:25.259
and has had to make do with
off-cuts and intestines

00:05:25.259 --> 00:05:27.800
and things like that-- anywhere
that's happened in the world,

00:05:27.800 --> 00:05:29.609
sausage has been invented.

00:05:29.609 --> 00:05:30.900
And that's what sausage is for.

00:05:30.900 --> 00:05:34.890
Sausage is for making
food out of stuff

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:38.990
that you don't necessarily
want to eat by itself, for lack

00:05:38.990 --> 00:05:40.217
of a better description.

00:05:40.217 --> 00:05:41.800
Wow, you'd think I
would have a better

00:05:41.800 --> 00:05:44.310
way of talking about
sausages, given

00:05:44.310 --> 00:05:46.460
that I wrote a book about it.

00:05:46.460 --> 00:05:49.020
No, but it's
evolved beyond that,

00:05:49.020 --> 00:05:51.995
to a point where I think
that sausage represents

00:05:51.995 --> 00:05:57.460
kind of everything good
about meat cookery,

00:05:57.460 --> 00:05:59.020
engineered to be easier.

00:05:59.020 --> 00:06:01.275
So what are the hard
things about cooking meat?

00:06:01.275 --> 00:06:03.650
You have to cook things to a
certain temperature for them

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:04.358
to still be good.

00:06:04.358 --> 00:06:07.400
They have to be cooked to medium
rare for a steak to be good.

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:09.932
Once you kind of go over
medium into well done,

00:06:09.932 --> 00:06:11.640
you kind of have this
tough piece of meat

00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:14.480
that's not as good
as you want it to be.

00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:17.640
Getting flavor into a steak,
or a piece of chicken breast,

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:20.440
or pork is a huge challenge.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:25.980
You marinate things, or
you brine things in order

00:06:25.980 --> 00:06:28.260
to make them flavorful.

00:06:28.260 --> 00:06:29.760
And then you've got
a whole industry

00:06:29.760 --> 00:06:31.710
of these sort of
prime cut meats,

00:06:31.710 --> 00:06:34.374
like wagyu or Kobe
beef, that are prized

00:06:34.374 --> 00:06:36.540
for, like, the marbling of
the fat, and how much fat

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:37.690
they have in them.

00:06:37.690 --> 00:06:39.660
Well, then, you've
got sausage, which

00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:41.220
you can cook to well done.

00:06:41.220 --> 00:06:43.510
You can season however
you want, and put as much

00:06:43.510 --> 00:06:46.190
seasoning as you want in it, and
it will be seasoned throughout.

00:06:46.190 --> 00:06:49.580
And you can put as much fucking
fat in there as you see fit.

00:06:49.580 --> 00:06:52.392
So, honestly, like,
sausage has come

00:06:52.392 --> 00:06:54.350
from this really humble
beginning to this thing

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:58.100
where, done right, you
can make it the highest

00:06:58.100 --> 00:06:59.070
form of meat cookery.

00:06:59.070 --> 00:07:00.692
So, anyway.

00:07:00.692 --> 00:07:01.650
The book is also funny.

00:07:01.650 --> 00:07:05.290
There's lots of poop
jokes and stuff.

00:07:05.290 --> 00:07:09.121
I highly recommend it for
Mother's Day or something.

00:07:09.121 --> 00:07:09.620
Yeah.

00:07:09.620 --> 00:07:12.400
So today, we're going
to make some sausage.

00:07:12.400 --> 00:07:14.743
How many people have made
sausage at home before?

00:07:14.743 --> 00:07:15.570
All right.

00:07:15.570 --> 00:07:19.350
Three to four people.

00:07:19.350 --> 00:07:23.017
There's sort of a whole
spectrum of difficulty

00:07:23.017 --> 00:07:24.350
when it comes to making sausage.

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:26.990
You can make really
difficult sausage--

00:07:26.990 --> 00:07:30.400
you can make mortadella, which
has to be sort of emulsified

00:07:30.400 --> 00:07:31.830
at a certain temperature.

00:07:31.830 --> 00:07:35.700
And you have to stud it with
pistachios and peppercorns.

00:07:35.700 --> 00:07:39.020
And it can be pretty difficult.

00:07:39.020 --> 00:07:40.690
And on the other
end of the spectrum,

00:07:40.690 --> 00:07:42.514
you can make sausage
really easily.

00:07:42.514 --> 00:07:44.180
And that's what we're
going to do today,

00:07:44.180 --> 00:07:47.727
because I'm not risking
anything difficult.

00:07:47.727 --> 00:07:50.060
So this is one of the things
I discovered when I started

00:07:50.060 --> 00:07:52.435
thinking about sausage, and
what to include in this book,

00:07:52.435 --> 00:07:55.330
was, like, oh, sausage is
niche, sausage is, too narrow,

00:07:55.330 --> 00:07:56.580
there's not that much sausage.

00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:59.430
And then I was, like, wait, I
eat sausage four times a week

00:07:59.430 --> 00:08:00.770
in the form of chorizo.

00:08:00.770 --> 00:08:05.330
If you live in the Bay Area,
in California in general,

00:08:05.330 --> 00:08:06.730
you've eaten chorizo.

00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:10.590
So chorizo is, you know,
probably the best known

00:08:10.590 --> 00:08:12.020
Mexican sausage.

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:15.270
And so, here to help
me make this today

00:08:15.270 --> 00:08:18.950
