You can use a spatula,
if you're scared, or not.

00:11:12.500 --> 00:11:14.000
ARALYN BEAUMONT:
Would you like one?

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:16.090
CHRIS YING: It really takes,
like, ten seconds on each--

00:11:16.090 --> 00:11:18.150
BRANDON CHALK: We have
good worker's comp here.

00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:18.940
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:11:18.940 --> 00:11:20.710
So you'll just press
this on the pan

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:22.240
for 10 seconds on each side.

00:11:22.240 --> 00:11:25.350
You'll see it starts to kind
of blister a little bit,

00:11:25.350 --> 00:11:27.900
as his fingertips
are currently doing.

00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:31.200
And it'll start to
smell incredible--

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:32.910
just, like, toasty and fruity.

00:11:32.910 --> 00:11:35.560
You can flip it over.

00:11:35.560 --> 00:11:37.870
This is just kind
of to-- I'm going

00:11:37.870 --> 00:11:40.530
to make this up-- this is
to "activate" the flavors.

00:11:40.530 --> 00:11:41.462
It doesn't do that.

00:11:41.462 --> 00:11:44.599
It doesn't do that at all.

00:11:44.599 --> 00:11:46.890
And so, you'll just do this
with each of these chilies.

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:51.111
This recipe, I think, calls for
something like 12 ancho chiles.

00:11:51.111 --> 00:11:51.920
Yeah, whatever.

00:11:51.920 --> 00:11:52.320
It doesn't matter.

00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:53.236
This is just for show.

00:11:53.236 --> 00:11:55.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:59.340
You'll soak them in
water for 20 minutes.

00:11:59.340 --> 00:12:01.300
You take a plate, and
you can push it on top

00:12:01.300 --> 00:12:03.630
and submerge them, so they
stay under and get soft.

00:12:03.630 --> 00:12:05.088
And then we're
going to pulse them.

00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:08.930
I got you.

00:12:08.930 --> 00:12:09.620
BRANDON CHALK:
Child safety lock.

00:12:09.620 --> 00:12:10.440
Thank you.

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:13.680
CHRIS YING: So just chilies
in there, without the water.

00:12:16.830 --> 00:12:18.580
Everybody's had chorizo, right?

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:21.070
So you're pretty aware
of the flavor profile.

00:12:21.070 --> 00:12:26.230
It's really, you know, a
little spicy, a little acidic,

00:12:26.230 --> 00:12:28.800
a little sour.

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:30.470
That's kind of a
hallmark of-- hold

00:12:30.470 --> 00:12:35.710
on one second-- of sausages
in other places as well.

00:12:35.710 --> 00:12:39.540
So in Southeast Asia, they'll
hang chiles to dry and ferment

00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:42.180
a little bit, so they get this
kind of sour taste to them.

00:12:42.180 --> 00:12:44.010
Chorizo has this
little sourness to it.

00:12:44.010 --> 00:12:45.700
It's not something
that we usually

00:12:45.700 --> 00:12:48.980
have in our sort of
American-style sausages.

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:50.720
But in the process
of making this book,

00:12:50.720 --> 00:12:55.704
it's been something I've
really enjoyed tasting.

00:12:55.704 --> 00:12:57.060
Right?

00:12:57.060 --> 00:13:00.010
So, here's what you're
going to do next.

00:13:00.010 --> 00:13:02.070
Bay leaves into the
mortar and pestle.

00:13:02.070 --> 00:13:03.980
BRANDON CHALK: Yup.

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:06.545
CHRIS YING: Throw these--
throw that in there, too.

00:13:06.545 --> 00:13:07.711
BRANDON CHALK: Smells fresh.

00:13:07.711 --> 00:13:10.420
CHRIS YING: Add thyme, marjoram.

00:13:10.420 --> 00:13:13.899
And just powderize that.

00:13:13.899 --> 00:13:15.940
BRANDON CHALK: So do you
have any favorite places

00:13:15.940 --> 00:13:16.935
for chorizo?

00:13:16.935 --> 00:13:19.310
CHRIS YING: Do I have
favorite places for chorizo?

00:13:19.310 --> 00:13:21.630
BRANDON CHALK: Or is
that a loaded question?

00:13:21.630 --> 00:13:23.380
CHRIS YING: I'm going
to help you out here

00:13:23.380 --> 00:13:30.190
with a little bit of salt.
So I spend a lot of time

00:13:30.190 --> 00:13:33.150
in the Mission District
in San Francisco,

00:13:33.150 --> 00:13:39.610
so the chorizo I eat usually
comes in very late night

00:13:39.610 --> 00:13:41.824
burrito form.

00:13:41.824 --> 00:13:43.240
But other than
that, I really like

00:13:43.240 --> 00:13:45.110
this thing called
a pombazo, which

00:13:45.110 --> 00:13:49.070
is like a torta filled with
potatoes and chorizo and crema,

00:13:49.070 --> 00:13:51.520
