thing into this red guajillo

00:13:51.520 --> 00:13:52.650
chili sauce.

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:55.460
And then they'll
griddle it crispy.

00:13:55.460 --> 00:13:57.139
It's pretty delicious.

00:13:57.139 --> 00:13:58.680
You're not having
too much luck here.

00:13:58.680 --> 00:13:59.981
Let me help you out a little it.

00:13:59.981 --> 00:14:01.772
ARALYN BEAUMONT: And
where do you get that?

00:14:02.549 --> 00:14:04.840
CHRIS YING: You can get that
at a place called La Torta

00:14:04.840 --> 00:14:07.599
Gorda, which is on 24th Street.

00:14:07.599 --> 00:14:09.140
I'm not having any
more luck, either.

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:10.598
We're going to
pretend that worked.

00:14:10.598 --> 00:14:25.530
So basically, herbs, oregano,
cinnamon, more oregano,

00:14:25.530 --> 00:14:28.790
for some reason.

00:14:28.790 --> 00:14:35.820
A little bit of ground
clove, salt, cider vinegar.

00:14:35.820 --> 00:14:38.390
And I imagine this is going
to need a little bit of water

00:14:38.390 --> 00:14:40.548
to get it going.

00:14:40.548 --> 00:14:42.532
AUDIENCE: Chris, why is
it important to pestle

00:14:42.532 --> 00:14:44.020
before you put it in?

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:47.105
CHRIS YING: Ideally, I wanted
to break down the bay leaves,

00:14:47.105 --> 00:14:48.896
so it was powdered,
and it didn't get-- you

00:14:48.896 --> 00:14:50.104
didn't have big chunks of it.

00:14:50.104 --> 00:14:51.172
But we failed.

00:14:51.172 --> 00:14:52.630
In life, sometimes,
you just gotta,

00:14:52.630 --> 00:14:54.695
like, accept your
failures and move on.

00:14:54.695 --> 00:14:56.987
You can't-- go for it, man.

00:14:56.987 --> 00:14:58.070
BRANDON CHALK: Pulse, or--

00:14:58.070 --> 00:14:59.736
CHRIS YING: Yeah,
pulse it a little bit.

00:14:59.736 --> 00:15:00.400
[PULSING]

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:02.201
Nah, just go for it.

00:15:02.201 --> 00:15:05.622
[GRINDING]

00:15:10.440 --> 00:15:17.160
So what we're making is
this kind of spice puree

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:21.007
that will basically
just fold in with pork.

00:15:21.007 --> 00:15:22.465
ARALYN BEAUMONT:
Want me to get it?

00:15:22.465 --> 00:15:23.964
CHRIS YING: Will
you grab that fork?

00:15:26.930 --> 00:15:30.762
So once this is smooth--
that seem smooth to you?

00:15:30.762 --> 00:15:31.595
BRANDON CHALK: Yeah.

00:15:31.595 --> 00:15:32.512
CHRIS YING: All right.

00:15:32.512 --> 00:15:34.595
I hope it's smooth, because
your next job is going

00:15:34.595 --> 00:15:35.855
to depend on it being smooth.

00:15:35.855 --> 00:15:36.730
We're going to push--

00:15:36.730 --> 00:15:38.313
BRANDON CHALK: That
looks pretty good.

00:15:38.313 --> 00:15:39.024
CHRIS YING: Ooh.

00:15:39.024 --> 00:15:40.690
This is my least
favorite part, and this

00:15:40.690 --> 00:15:42.630
is why it's helpful
to have a helper here.

00:15:42.630 --> 00:15:44.130
BRANDON CHALK: An
unassuming helper.

00:15:44.130 --> 00:15:44.838
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:15:55.590 --> 00:15:59.360
ARALYN BEAUMONT: Chris, do you
prefer green or red chorizo?

00:15:59.360 --> 00:16:01.222
CHRIS YING: Oh, that's
a great question.

00:16:01.222 --> 00:16:02.930
We're actually making
two chorizos today.

00:16:02.930 --> 00:16:04.820
We're making a red and
