Why don't you scrape off here?

00:17:33.245 --> 00:17:34.620
And so, for the
purposes of this,

00:17:34.620 --> 00:17:36.720
we're going to pretend that
you finished doing this,

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:37.520
and we're going to move on here.

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:38.856
BRANDON CHALK: Perfect.

00:17:38.856 --> 00:17:39.240
ARALYN BEAUMONT:
Here, I can take that.

00:17:39.240 --> 00:17:41.656
CHRIS YING: So, basically, you
just want to get out, like,

00:17:41.656 --> 00:17:43.180
the big chunks of nonsense.

00:17:43.180 --> 00:17:46.270
Give me the-- let
me just hold this.

00:17:46.270 --> 00:17:49.200
You want to get rid of the
stringy bits of the bay leaf

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:53.490
that are stuck on there, any
unprocessed chunks of chile,

00:17:53.490 --> 00:17:55.090
and things like that.

00:17:55.090 --> 00:17:58.080
And then you're going to have
this relatively smooth puree.

00:17:58.080 --> 00:18:02.850
So this is the part that I
feel like is pretty neat.

00:18:02.850 --> 00:18:05.360
You don't need the
KitchenAid attachment.

00:18:05.360 --> 00:18:08.070
You don't need a meat grinder,
or anything like that.

00:18:08.070 --> 00:18:11.340
You can really make an
[INAUDIBLE] sausage out

00:18:11.340 --> 00:18:12.950
of your food processor.

00:18:12.950 --> 00:18:18.029
So pork shoulder, which you
can supplement with fat back.

00:18:18.029 --> 00:18:19.820
If you go to your
butcher and you ask them,

00:18:19.820 --> 00:18:22.580
they're never going to
have it out for you to buy.

00:18:22.580 --> 00:18:24.540
But sausage--
generally, you know,

00:18:24.540 --> 00:18:30.464
you want this percentage between
30% fat and 70% lean meat.

00:18:30.464 --> 00:18:32.130
So if your pork
shoulder's not that fat,

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:34.390
you can ask them for fat
back, and they'll usually

00:18:34.390 --> 00:18:35.660
have some in the back.

00:18:35.660 --> 00:18:37.910
Just the other day, I bought
some, and I took it home,

00:18:37.910 --> 00:18:39.570
and it was rotten.

00:18:39.570 --> 00:18:42.710
So check your fat back
before you get home.

00:18:42.710 --> 00:18:44.592
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:44.592 --> 00:18:47.320
AUDIENCE: Lesson of the day.

00:18:47.320 --> 00:18:50.440
CHRIS YING: Such an unhelpful
lesson to anybody at all.

00:18:50.440 --> 00:18:52.460
Freezing the meat
really helps when you're

00:18:52.460 --> 00:18:54.590
doing it in a food processor.

00:18:57.860 --> 00:19:00.400
It keeps it from kind of
getting, like, squishing

00:19:00.400 --> 00:19:01.744
instead of slicing.

00:19:01.744 --> 00:19:03.660
You'll be able to kind
of mince the meat more.

00:19:03.660 --> 00:19:05.486
You kind of want
this coarse texture

00:19:05.486 --> 00:19:07.485
to it, which is actually
the benefit of doing it

00:19:07.485 --> 00:19:09.910
in a proper grinder-- you're
going to get an even grind,

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:13.350
an even coarseness,
according to what you want.

00:19:13.350 --> 00:19:16.195
When you do it here,
the other day, I

00:19:16.195 --> 00:19:18.772
had huge cubes of fat
left in my sausage,

00:19:18.772 --> 00:19:20.480
and other parts were
kind of just pureed.

00:19:20.480 --> 00:19:24.721
But, that's fine, because I'm
telling you do it this way.

00:19:24.721 --> 00:19:27.440
BRANDON CHALK: And how long
should you generally freeze it?

00:19:27.440 --> 00:19:29.523
CHRIS YING: You do want
to freeze it just until it

00:19:29.523 --> 00:19:30.640
gets kind of crisp edges.

00:19:30.640 --> 00:19:31.390
BRANDON CHALK: OK.

00:19:31.390 --> 00:19:36.250
CHRIS YING: So not so it's hard,
but just so it's not squishy,

00:19:36.250 --> 00:19:37.970
like my body.

00:19:37.970 --> 00:19:39.191
[PULSING]

00:19:39.191 --> 00:19:40.920
And so here's a
pulsing situation.

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:43.580
[PULSING]

00:19:43.580 --> 00:19:47.910
You don't want to get into the
food bolus situation, where

00:19:47.910 --> 00:19:50.102
you've just got this
big ball spinning around

00:19:50.102 --> 00:19:51.060
in your food processor.

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:53.420
And doing in batches also helps.

00:19:53.420 --> 00:20:00.490
So you're just trying to get
a pretty coarse grind on it.

00:20:00.490 --> 00:20:01.740
That looks pretty good, right?

00:20:01.740 --> 00:20:02.050
I don't know.

00:20:02.050 --> 00:20:02.190
BRANDON CHALK: Yeah.

00:20:02.190 --> 00:20:03.280
I think it works.

00:20:03.280 --> 00:20:06.430
CHRIS YING: And here-- why
don't you do the next batch.

00:20:09.730 --> 00:20:11.055
And this is basically it.

00:20:11.055 --> 00:20:13.730
You pulse the meat until
it looks like sausage.

00:20:13.730 --> 00:20:15.230
Every knows what
sausage looks like.

00:20:15.230 --> 00:20:18.600
Just do it until it
looks like sausage.

00:20:18.600 --> 00:20:22.280
And then mix it
with your spice mix.

00:20:22.280 --> 00:20:23.420
Cover it, refrigerate it.

00:20:23.420 --> 00:20:26.170
Let it kind of absorb all
that flavor overnight.

00:20:26.170 --> 00:20:28.030
And then literally, that's it.

00:20:28.030 --> 00:20:29.220
Then you have chorizo.

00:20:29.220 --> 00:20:33.021
[PULSING]

00:20:40.500 --> 00:20:41.000
Yeah, dude.

00:20:45.020 --> 00:20:46.490
Yeah, let's call it.

00:20:46.490 --> 00:20:46.990
Beautiful.

00:20:52.230 --> 00:20:54.308
ARALYN BEAUMONT: Ew. [LAUGHING]

00:20:55.760 --> 00:21:00.520
CHRIS YING: It's not the most
glamorous of cooking processes,

00:21:00.520 --> 00:21:02.094
but, you know-- works.

00:21:02.094 --> 00:21:02.760
That's whatever.

