It just means, like,
somebody ate some blue cheese

00:33:05.583 --> 00:33:07.820
while they were making
your sausage, or whatever.

00:33:07.820 --> 00:33:11.130
But in Germany-- I
think specifically,

00:33:11.130 --> 00:33:15.180
we were in Munich.

00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:17.610
And I think it's actually
an Austrian sausage called

00:33:17.610 --> 00:33:20.060
the Kasekrainer, which
is a cheese sausage.

00:33:20.060 --> 00:33:22.740
And we sliced into it,
and was sort of again

00:33:22.740 --> 00:33:25.150
disappointed-- I was like,
oh, there's no cheese in here.

00:33:25.150 --> 00:33:29.000
And then miraculously, sort of
out of these invisible pores,

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:33.090
all this melted cheese started
oozing out of the sausage.

00:33:33.090 --> 00:33:34.990
And it was the most
incredible thing.

00:33:34.990 --> 00:33:40.220
And I asked Eli Cairo
from Olympia Provisions

00:33:40.220 --> 00:33:41.410
sort of about how it's made.

00:33:41.410 --> 00:33:43.493
And it all has to do with
kind of the temperature,

00:33:43.493 --> 00:33:45.600
and making sure you
are mixing this sausage

00:33:45.600 --> 00:33:49.590
at a really cold temperature,
so the cheese doesn't distribute

00:33:49.590 --> 00:33:50.470
into the meat.

00:33:50.470 --> 00:33:51.560
But that was amazing.

00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:53.350
I couldn't get enough of that.

00:33:53.350 --> 00:33:57.330
It was the best cheese
sausage I'd ever had.

00:33:57.330 --> 00:33:59.750
So, yeah.

00:33:59.750 --> 00:34:00.800
I don't know.

00:34:00.800 --> 00:34:02.050
Anybody else want a sticker?

00:34:02.050 --> 00:34:04.010
Was a great question?

00:34:04.010 --> 00:34:07.360
AUDIENCE: I want to know
about "Lucky Peach."

00:34:07.360 --> 00:34:09.380
Are you planning on
taking over the world?

00:34:09.380 --> 00:34:13.592
What's the next
step in domination?

00:34:13.592 --> 00:34:14.300
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:34:14.300 --> 00:34:16.300
So, I mean, "Lucky
Peach" started, honestly,

00:34:16.300 --> 00:34:18.872
as this crazy little whim
that three of us had.

00:34:18.872 --> 00:34:20.330
We thought we could
make a magazine

00:34:20.330 --> 00:34:24.150
and just focus on the
things that we thought

00:34:24.150 --> 00:34:25.310
were funny and interesting.

00:34:25.310 --> 00:34:27.550
And it turned out that
a lot of other people

00:34:27.550 --> 00:34:30.960
found the same things
interesting as we did.

00:34:30.960 --> 00:34:33.969
Like I said, originally, we
were going to do "101 Easy Asian

00:34:33.969 --> 00:34:36.742
Recipes" as a joke.

00:34:36.742 --> 00:34:38.200
But once we found
this audience, it

00:34:38.200 --> 00:34:41.900
was kind of like, now we
should do this for real.

00:34:41.900 --> 00:34:45.850
So cookbooks-- we
went five years

00:34:45.850 --> 00:34:49.250
without a proper website,
which I don't think

00:34:49.250 --> 00:34:51.880
was smart in retrospect.

00:34:51.880 --> 00:34:53.600
But we're rebuilding
our website.

00:34:53.600 --> 00:34:56.010
Yeah, we're trying to grow it.

00:34:56.010 --> 00:35:01.310
And in the way that we
try to make the magazine

00:35:01.310 --> 00:35:05.240
this big lush object
that people want to save,

00:35:05.240 --> 00:35:08.300
we kind of want to play to
the forms that we expand to.

00:35:08.300 --> 00:35:09.960
So when we do digital
things, we hope

00:35:09.960 --> 00:35:14.440
that we're not just online
for the sake of being online.

00:35:14.440 --> 00:35:17.530
You know, we're not just
making a "Lucky Peach" app,

00:35:17.530 --> 00:35:19.090
because everyone
else has an app.

00:35:19.090 --> 00:35:26.720
So, yeah-- very slow domination
of a tiny corner of the world

00:35:26.720 --> 00:35:28.541
is our plan.

00:35:28.541 --> 00:35:29.290
You got questions?

00:35:29.290 --> 00:35:30.123
BRANDON CHALK: Yeah.

00:35:30.123 --> 00:35:32.340
Of course I have questions.

00:35:32.340 --> 00:35:34.870
So you had mentioned that
"The Wurst of Lucky Peach"

00:35:34.870 --> 00:35:37.760
is the first of a series of
single-subject cookbooks.

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:38.784
What other--

00:35:38.784 --> 00:35:39.700
CHRIS YING: Oh my God.

00:35:39.700 --> 00:35:41.310
This guy's the best.

00:35:41.310 --> 00:35:42.520
Brandon's the best.

00:35:42.520 --> 00:35:46.580
So our very next book is
called "All About Eggs."

00:35:46.580 --> 00:35:48.660
And I think the
subtitle I came up

00:35:48.660 --> 00:35:51.070
was like, "Everything We
Know about the World's Most

00:35:51.070 --> 00:35:52.730
Important Food."

00:35:52.730 --> 00:35:54.605
So it'll be eggs-- will be next.

00:35:54.605 --> 00:35:56.480
And then after that,
it's kind of in the air.

00:35:56.480 --> 00:36:00.040
I would love to do more books
in the way of those "Time Life"

00:36:00.040 --> 00:36:05.127
books, where you sort of study
certain cuisines of the world.

00:36:05.127 --> 00:36:07.710
My mom has been bothering me to
do a book about-- she's always

00:36:07.710 --> 00:36:09.606
like, Chris, do a
book about coconut.

00:36:09.606 --> 00:36:13.127
And I'm like, Mom, no one
gives a shit about coconut.

00:36:13.127 --> 00:36:15.210
ARALYN BEAUMONT: But you're
realizing she's right.

00:36:15.210 --> 00:36:16.130
CHRIS YING: I know, right?

00:36:16.130 --> 00:36:17.130
ARALYN BEAUMONT: The
more you think about it--

00:36:17.130 --> 00:36:17.830
BRANDON CHALK: Like,
coconut water--

00:36:17.830 --> 00:36:19.150
I feel like that's
gotten really big

00:36:19.150 --> 00:36:20.110
in the last couple of years.

00:36:20.110 --> 00:36:20.885
CHRIS YING: Yeah,
coconut water and curry.

00:36:20.885 --> 00:36:23.380
Everyone loves curry,
so-- stupid moms.

00:36:23.380 --> 00:36:25.990
ARALYN BEAUMONT:
Coconut desserts.

00:36:25.990 --> 00:36:27.480
CHRIS YING: Coconut desserts?

00:36:27.480 --> 00:36:29.594
My god.

00:36:29.594 --> 00:36:30.885
BRANDON CHALK: Coconut ketchup.

00:36:30.885 --> 00:36:32.444
CHRIS YING: No coconut ketchup.

00:36:32.444 --> 00:36:34.360
But yeah, that's sort
of next on the pipeline.

00:36:34.360 --> 00:36:35.120
I don't know.

00:36:35.120 --> 00:36:38.530
It's a fun thing, because
just like with sausages,

00:36:38.530 --> 00:36:42.280
you think it's this very
specific, narrow topic.

00:36:42.280 --> 00:36:46.340
And then you kind of realize
that having these constraints

00:36:46.340 --> 00:36:47.940
lets you be more
creative in how you

00:36:47.940 --> 00:36:51.930
approach a subject, how you come
up with things to talk about.

00:36:51.930 --> 00:36:55.360
So yeah, I don't know-- I'm
looking forward to other books.

00:36:55.360 --> 00:36:57.110
AUDIENCE: So you claimed
to not be a chef,

00:36:57.110 --> 00:36:59.470
but what got you into this
food space in general?

00:36:59.470 --> 00:37:02.910
Was it parents cooking,
or something else?

00:37:02.910 --> 00:37:04.490
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:37:04.490 --> 00:37:11.790
I personally grew up in a
little bit of a food family.

00:37:11.790 --> 00:37:14.790
My mom owned a Mexican
restaurant and two ice cream

00:37:14.790 --> 00:37:16.880
stores.

00:37:16.880 --> 00:37:19.325
But I think a lot of
first generation--

00:37:19.325 --> 00:37:20.960
am I first generation?

00:37:20.960 --> 00:37:22.700
Whatever generation
of Asian person

00:37:22.700 --> 00:37:26.520
I am-- I think a lot of us
sort of realized in the last 10

00:37:26.520 --> 00:37:30.760
or 15 years-- the way we
grew up, the things we ate,

00:37:30.760 --> 00:37:33.900
the familiar ways that
we ate with our families,

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:39.040
had some kind of value
or interest to people.

00:37:39.040 --> 00:37:40.830
And when I got to
college, I sort of

00:37:40.830 --> 00:37:44.456
started sharing some of the
things that I ate as a kid,

00:37:44.456 --> 00:37:46.580
with my roommates and
friends and things like that.

00:37:46.580 --> 00:37:50.340
And I cooked in a restaurant
for four or five years.

00:37:50.340 --> 00:37:55.260
I helped open Mission Street
Food and Mission Chinese Food.

00:37:55.260 --> 00:37:57.510
But I never really
wanted these two worlds

00:37:57.510 --> 00:37:59.830
to come together--
the writing thing

00:37:59.830 --> 00:38:02.450
I was doing at this
company called McSweeney's,

00:38:02.450 --> 00:38:04.800
and the food stuff.

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:06.600
And then I met Dave
Chang and Peter Meehan,

00:38:06.600 --> 00:38:11.480
and they kind of
convinced me to do this.

00:38:11.480 --> 00:38:14.540
And now I'm here making
chorizo for people at Google.

00:38:14.540 --> 00:38:16.820
And I just, like, I
don't know what happened.

00:38:16.820 --> 00:38:19.520
At some point, everything
went off the rails,

00:38:19.520 --> 00:38:20.340
and now I do this.

00:38:20.340 --> 00:38:23.110
But yeah, no-- I mean, I
think that for me, it's

00:38:23.110 --> 00:38:27.940
been a really long process
of-- or really, fortunate

00:38:27.940 --> 00:38:33.100
process-- that me
discovering what food meant

00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:36.150
to me as a person coincided
with everyone kind of starting

00:38:36.150 --> 00:38:38.840
to care more about food
and paying attention

00:38:38.840 --> 00:38:41.320
to how food plays into
our own American culture.

00:38:41.320 --> 00:38:45.040
So yeah.

00:38:45.040 --> 00:38:46.150
All right.

00:38:46.150 --> 00:38:47.020
Any last questions?

00:38:47.020 --> 00:38:48.045
Do you want a sticker?

00:38:48.045 --> 00:38:49.092
Give the man a sticker.

00:38:52.381 --> 00:38:52.880
All right.

00:38:52.880 --> 00:38:53.935
Well, here we go.

00:38:53.935 --> 00:38:54.435
Question.

00:38:58.720 --> 00:39:01.310
AUDIENCE: Have you ever
made weird sausage stuff?

00:39:01.310 --> 00:39:04.340
Like the ones with
intestines inside?

00:39:04.340 --> 00:39:06.340
CHRIS YING: Have I ever
made weird sausage stuff

00:39:06.340 --> 00:39:07.806
with intestines inside?

00:39:07.806 --> 00:39:08.798
AUDIENCE: Or whater.

00:39:12.380 --> 00:39:15.610
CHRIS YING: I've not personally
made the crazy, crazy sausages,

00:39:15.610 --> 00:39:19.780
that are like-- there are
sausages, like she said,

00:39:19.780 --> 00:39:24.120
that are intestines stuffed with
more intestines and other organ

00:39:24.120 --> 00:39:26.830
meats, and really just
made from the off-cuts

00:39:26.830 --> 00:39:27.720
and things like that.

00:39:27.720 --> 00:39:31.400
And andouillette is made
from the lower intestine,

00:39:31.400 --> 00:39:35.437
and is kind of prized for how
poopy it smells and tastes.

00:39:35.437 --> 00:39:36.770
I haven't made too much of that.

00:39:36.770 --> 00:39:42.490
But I've been making sausage
since I was in college,

00:39:42.490 --> 00:39:44.470
and really found
it to be rewarding,

00:39:44.470 --> 00:39:48.574
once you have kind of a rough
formula for what goes in it.

00:39:48.574 --> 00:39:50.240
You can just sort of
mess around and put

00:39:50.240 --> 00:39:51.364
whatever you want in there.

00:39:51.364 --> 00:39:55.040
So at Thanksgiving time,
I make a turkey sausage

00:39:55.040 --> 00:39:57.910
with green Szechuan
peppercorn and all this, like,

00:39:57.910 --> 00:40:00.750
funky-- it's really tingly,
and numbing, and spicy.

00:40:00.750 --> 00:40:04.410
And that was just kind
of pulled out of nowhere.

00:40:04.410 --> 00:40:05.970
So it's fun to just do whatever.

00:40:05.970 --> 00:40:07.670
And that's in the book.

00:40:07.670 --> 00:40:10.699
AUDIENCE: So out of all the
ones that you make at home

00:40:10.699 --> 00:40:12.490
for your own personal
use, which one do you

00:40:12.490 --> 00:40:14.086
find you making the most of?

00:40:17.135 --> 00:40:19.910
CHRIS YING: I would
say, because I make it

00:40:19.910 --> 00:40:23.170
on such a consistent basis,
that sort of weird Thanksgiving

00:40:23.170 --> 00:40:28.740
turkey tingling sausage is
the one I make most regularly.

00:40:28.740 --> 00:40:31.531
And I have this whole
break down system.

00:40:31.531 --> 00:40:33.530
I describe it in the book,
too, where it's like,

00:40:33.530 --> 00:40:35.654
one turkey breast goes
here, another one goes here,

00:40:35.654 --> 00:40:37.260
and then the legs go this way.

00:40:37.260 --> 00:40:39.380
So Thanksgiving
turkey at my house

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:43.290
is like a weird smorgasbord.

00:40:43.290 --> 00:40:45.537
Other than that,
the loose sausages

00:40:45.537 --> 00:40:47.120
are the easiest and
most approachable.

00:40:47.120 --> 00:40:48.910
So you can make
them super often.

00:40:48.910 --> 00:40:51.846
You're going to make this over
and over and over again now.

00:40:51.846 --> 00:40:55.010
You know, you can make
breakfast sausage really easily.

00:40:55.010 --> 00:40:58.502
Those are probably the
most approachable ones.

00:40:58.502 --> 00:40:59.074
Yeah.

00:40:59.074 --> 00:40:59.990
FEMALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:40:59.990 --> 00:41:01.300
Thank you very much.

00:41:01.300 --> 00:41:04.600
[APPLAUSE]

00:41:04.600 --> 00:41:06.450
CHRIS YING: Thanks, guys.

